  "answer": "Iqbal's poem *Larkiyan parh rahi hain angrezi* (Bang-e-Dara Part 3, ch. 27) adopts a sharply satirical tone, mocking the colonial-era enthusiasm for Western education among Indian Muslims as a misguided \"path to salvation\" that elevates English learning and Western manners while scorning Eastern traditions.[^1] The poem's rhetorical questions—\"What scene will this drama show? / The gaze awaits the curtain to rise\"—build irony, implying impending cultural tragedy or farce from such blind imitation.[^1]\n\nIn contrast, *Bachay Ki Dua* (Bang-e-Dara Part 1, ch. 16), framed as a child's innocent prayer, conveys a devout, aspirational tone focused on moral and spiritual self-improvement through education.[^2] The child beseeches God to make their life \"like a candle's flare\" that dispels darkness, a \"moth\" drawn to the \"candle of knowledge,\" and a source of pride for the homeland, while championing the poor and seeking protection from wrong.[^2] Education here is idealized as righteous pursuit intertwined with faith, service, and love for the vulnerable, without Western specificity.\n\nThe tones diverge starkly on early education: *Larkiyan*'s biting critique warns against cultural erosion via imposed Western curricula (notably for girls), while *Bachay Ki Dua*'s pious optimism envisions education as holistic enlightenment rooted in Islamic values and national upliftment.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 27: \"Larkiyan parh rahi hain angrezi\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/27-larkiyan-parh-rahi-hain-angrezi/translation/#p-289582)).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 16: \"Bachay Ki Dua\" ([chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/)).",
